                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>SAMUEL GWILLIAMS. On the 1st of August, about half-past three o'clock in the afternoon, when I came home, I found the prisoner in the house. I missed my watch, which I had left safe. As I was taking him before a magistrate, he told me if I took up two boys I should get my watch again. My wife was at home - She is ill.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-301-person2088">
                  JOHN 
                  BRANCH
               <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2088" type="surname" value="BRANCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2088" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2088" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in <placeName id="t18180909-301-crimeloc1656">Harford-place, Haggerston</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-301-crimeloc1656" type="placeName" value="Harford-place, Haggerston"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-301-crimeloc1656" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-301-off1654 t18180909-301-crimeloc1656"></join>-the prosecutor lives there also. I saw the prisoner come out of the prosecutor's house, with the watch in his hand; he ran off - I was very near him; the watch appeared white. Mr. Davis, the publican, took him. I do not know what he did with the watch.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-301-person2089">
                  JOHN 
                  WELLS
               <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2089" type="surname" value="WELLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2089" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2089" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Haggerston. About three o'clock in the afternoon, I saw the prisoner sitting on a bench with two other boys, opposite the prosecutor's house - I was sitting on the same bench myself, but farther on. I afterwards saw the prisoner run out of the prosecutor's house with a silver watch in his hand. I called out Stop thief! and told Mr. Davis, he stopped him. Before he was stopped, he had passed the two boys who had been with him - They said they would run round and meet him; he was within a yard of them. I kept sight of him all the while, but do not know what was done with the watch.</p>
               <p>SAMUEL GWILLIAMS re-examined. My watch was a silver one; it had a black ribbon, and was worth 30s.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-301-person2090">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HENRY WELLS
               <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2090" type="surname" value="HENRY WELLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2090" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-person2090" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner sitting on a bench opposite the prosecutor's house, with some other boys. I saw him give the watch to two boys; he went round the corner of Davis's house, into a brick-field; Davis ran out, and took him there.</p>
               <p>Q. What colour was the watch - A. White, with a black ribbon.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180909-301-verdict1657" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18180909-301-verdict1657" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 13.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180909-301-punish1658" type="punishmentDescription">
